{"questionId":"17440","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following shape consists of three arcs of a circle, each with centre at the opposite vertex of an equilateral triangle as shown in the diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/80a9f1d313fdda5574e0c2067c0da251080f7118.png\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">For this shape, calculate</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>the perimeter.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>each arc has length&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"r\\theta&nbsp; = 6 \\times \\frac{\\pi }{3} = 2\\pi \\,\\left( { = 6.283 \\ldots } \\right)\"> <mi>r</mi> <mi>θ</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>6</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mfrac> <mi>π</mi> <mn>3</mn> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mi>π</mi> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>6.283</mn> <mo>…</mo> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>perimeter is therefore&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"6\\pi \\,\\left( { = 18.8} \\right)\"> <mn>6</mn> <mi>π</mi> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>18.8</mn> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span> (cm)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17440","referenceCode":"19N.2.AHL.TZ0.H_4a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"the perimeter.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.4—Circle: radians, arcs, sectors"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}